    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n7391" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">πέλω</span></b> , <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">πέλει</span>, ipf. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">πέλεν</span>, aor.
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἔπλε</span>, and <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">πέλομαι</span>, imp. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">πέλευ</span>, ipf.
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">πέλοντο</span>, iter. 2 sing. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">πελέσκεο</span>, aor. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἔπλεο,
            ἔπλευ, ἔπλετο</span>: a poetic synonym of <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">εἶναι, γίγνεσθαι</span>, perhaps originally containing some idea
          of motion (versari), but in Homer simply <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">to be</span>, <i><span class="en">Il. 3.3</span></i>, <i><span class="en">Il.
            12.271</span></i>, <i><span class="en">Od. 13.60</span></i>, <i><span class="en">Il. 5.729</span></i>; the aor. has pres. signif.
          (like <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἔφυ</span> in Attic), <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">εἰ δή ῥ̓ ἐθέλεις καί τοι φίλον ἔπλετο θῡμῷ</span>,
          ‘and it pleases thee,’ <i><span class="en">Il. 14.337</span></i>,
            <i><span class="en">Od. 13.145</span></i>, etc.</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
